annotation: I started off with intentions to open up the d-file.
He responded with e5 a common opening move.
I protected my future pawn placement and began with a three or four knight opening.
He protected the piece that I was threatening.
I stopped congestion of the queen. Best to get this out of the way for my future plans will need it. Also I threatened the pawn- now with 2 pieces. Not leaving my pawn en prise however.
He took the bait...I mean piece...as I planned out my next move.
I traded off and took his pawn in revenge.
He then took my knight with his. It took me long to understand that at this point my queen could still attack him. It also helped my plan greatly.
I took him without a second glance.
He moved out. A move I saw coming. He was planning on taking me with his Dark Squared Bishop.
I moved out my bishop to allow my rook an opening in case of instantaneous attack however my knight still stood in the way.
As if I predicted the future he attacked.
I easily defended staying off the back line to keep my plan intact.
He developed his knight nonthreatening.

I developed mine in return. Serving a double purpose also opening my rook. A better move would have been to develop towards the center however. Still though I opened outside taking the enemies DSB (dark squared bishop) out of play for the future.
Gone he performed a trade and it was off the board.
I decided this would be okay. Although the b-file was open it was not going to be a large threat.
He put my queen in danger and I had to act.
Still remaining off the back line my plan was in motion. My next mission was to remove his d-pawn.
His knight threatening me yet again I was in danger.
Back to the running block I returned to original position.
Forking my Rook and queen I knew i was in trouble.
I pulled my rook in any other case a queen would be necessary however for this I needed that rook.
Crucial mistake not noticing. He pulled his d-pawn out.
I threatened his knight actually in an attempt to move the d-pawn.
Blunder he took the bishop not the queen. Oblivious he lost himself the game.

Checkmate. I took his unprotected queen and he had nowhere to go. Good game Millionaire if you had noticed that it would have gone differently. Good game. Thanks everyone hope you enjoyed. Stay tuned for the next one.
I started out thinking about an irregular move-set. The Queen's Gambit.
He began by developing his king-side knight.
I continued my Gambit like moves and opened up my queen for development.
He placed his protected pawn on d5. This allowed me to know he wanted a fast paced game.
I took him offering a trade off.
He completed the trade but minimized his teams development.
I threatened his knight with my king's pawn
He moved away and both of us were still yet to develop.
I began with a slight variation to a 3 knights defense.
He moved out to offer a different game set in my opinion
I stayed on the path to my three knights defense.
He pinned my knight and queen.
I forced him to take action livening up the pace.
He took my knight off my hands for a trade.
I accepted the trade and developed my queen.
He took my pawn ruining my defense.
I threatened his queen and pinned his knight.
The queen nicely backed off. Ready at any moment for a queen's trade.
I setup for a fork between his king and rook.
He further developed his pieces and the Queen's side of the board looked more like a stable.
I took his knight with no further threat.
He Traded of the queens evenly and I was ready for mate.
I traded off. Devising my plan.
He took my bishop and I decided to continue.
A well placed rook stopped his king from motion. That should have a been a sure sign of foresighted mate.
He threatened my knight. I was planning on allowing him to take it so that I could mate him.
I still protected though not seeming suspicious.
He took no mercy and my sacrifice was a completion. At this point it wouldn't make a difference what I lost.
Mate. I killed his pawn for revenge and finished off the rest of that maniac. Good game CM. I hope to play again soon. Hope you enjoyed it Everybody. Thanks.

"Rosselsprung" was the codename of a German naval operation in World War Two in which the battleship "Tirpitz" sortied to intercept an Allied arctic convoy.  The operation was a success for the Germans.  "Rosselsprung" refers to the knight's move in chess.
I had no affinity with the "Kriegsmarine's" interests.  And since my opponent was around 1650 I wanted a good game.
We have here a queen's gambit declined with black playing a quick h6.
I often play this move in queen's gambit variations.  While it does close the dsb's diagonal I in mind b3 and bb2.
Everything looks to be proceeding normally here.  My last annotated game had been a disaster and I kept this in mind as I selected my moves.
Part of the problem in my last game had been that I was failing to see the board.  I had put the blinders on.  "Rosselsprung" would have to be more than just a cheap tactical threat.
And so I sortied on.  The bishop on b2 looks like it may be good even though the opening here identifies it as a closed game.
Later this move would prove a mistake as bd3 would have been stronger.
Another mistake.  I think taking cd is fine but qc2 or even qd3 was probably better.  Here it proves to be hemmed in by the pawn chain.
I consider this move pretty debatable given the pawn on d5 and white's a2 and b3 pawns.

Black finally looks to open the board.  In this position I did not mind c4 or cxd.  I decide to castle kingside even though I often prefer to castle queenside.  I am thinking the rooks will be good on c and d.
Maybe I didn't have to take the knight with qc2.  But after dxe and ne5 bc4 seems possible.
Nc4 also appears strong but white has weakened the light squares around the king and I wanted to play bh5 to threaten winning the exchange.
nxe7 rxe7 was possible but black's dsb is not looking like a very good piece.  I think the decision not to take was sound.
With threats of d5.
Against d5 and threatening qxh5.
Obvious threats of dxc followed by rac1.
Here I just went ahead and played dxc since I didn't think the knight on b4 was going to be that great.
In this position rac1 may have been better.  I am threatening to win the exchange and to take nxe6.  Also I am defending d3.
He protects against the ne6 threat but is loosing the exchange.

In this position white looks to be doing well. He is ahead in material has a good knight on f4 has good control of the c and d files and has a good bishop on b2.  Black by contrast is going to have to move his queen to an inactive square and has a knight with no real prospects now that d3 is stronger for white after nf4.
I don't think this move is that bad although it is admittedly not great.  Black can just play bg6 although this will certainly lead to simplifications.
Threatening rdd7 after black defends the bishop and the f5 bishop is dealt with.
Black tries to create complications with this move.
And white is winning with qxg7# inevitable.
My chess has been suffering.  I am getting too lazy to thoroughly analyze tactical sequences.  What follows is a transcription of a game I recently had playing in Santa Cruz.

My opponent was rated around 1600 FIDE.  I wanted to get a good position out of the opening and I placed the bishop classically.  I generally dislike playing Indian systems because of the fianchettoed bishop.  I don't like using the bishop in this way.  With c5 my opponent is playing a Queen's gambit opening.
This advance will clearly have major implications.  Black is now committed to a defense of the d5 square and will probably have to play e6.  White could attempt to liberate with b3 or even e4.
I think nc3 is sound but maybe nd2 was a better continuation.

There has been some very informative discussion in the comments to my last game about the advisability of h3 or a3.  It seems to be a question of timing.  In this position white has problems if black is able to play Ng4.  So the provocation of bg4 looks to be timely.
After 8 moves I rate my development sufficient to begin staging for an attack on the black king.

The attack is launched but will it be too early.  I thought black will be able to defend this if he plays correctly.  But no one ever plays correctly.  I thought that nxe5 was going to be find for white after be5.
I do see the tactic of hxg if white plays an immediate g5.
Another committal pawn move.  I think gxh ends up looking not so great for white.
After the knight sac white prepares an aggressive attack after qf3.  If here ne4 then nxe4 dxe and probably f4.
I don't think the knight is that great here.  It does appear to have some purpose attacking f2 and e3.  But black may have difficulty getting it into action.
Where qf3 was obviously superior.  This is the kind of mistake that causes me to have doubts about my game.  Of course it was blitz but this is just an embarrassing oversight.
And again I don't play qf3.  Seemingly this game was a bad choice to annotate.
This is just terrible.  I am going to the club in Phoenix next week for an invitational and I need to play a lot better even in blitz.
Finally the merciful 19) qf3.
How not bc7+.  This honestly may be the poorest level of play of any annotation of mine.
I judged this superior to bxd6+ but it may not have been.  At this point time was very short.
From this point white probably had winning continuations I did not play.

And here as I crudely gain material time expires on my opponent's clock.  I think the point here is not to overcomplicate things by being too ambitious when on the attack.  And to mentally step away from the position from time to time so that when I return obvious features of the position are apparent.
I opened with clear intentions to take out a rook.
He began with a slight variation to a common opening move. This caught my attention.
I decided to hide my plan by symmetrizing...which happens to be a word. And hoped he wouldn't notice.
He moved out his bishop threatening king-side bishop pawn- and looking suspiciously like a 4-move checkmate.

I decided to attack the left side rook after consideration. I did this because after planning out the enemies moves I realized it would prevent the checkmate on me a turn too soon. Giving me no chance at taking the queen.
He moved out his queen in a motion different then I had seen before. It almost got me but I decided to prepare.
I moved out my f-pawn stopping the mate.
He took my bishop for a trade
I accepted the trade and continued on my original plan. However I then learned that the adversaries white bishop would have to be drawn out.
He stole my plan and took my rook easily.
I trapped his piece however could not threaten the queen.
He developed his rook realizing he could not escape easily.
I offered a trade because otherwise it could have ended much worse.
He accepted the trade and put me in check.
I escaped check 'narrowly' and killed off the queen. However I was trapped behind a wall of pawns.
He developed towards the middle not giving the best position but stopping my plans for the rook attack.
I bellied up to the knight planning a check in my future and forking the rook and king.
He noticed and took advantage of the position.
I moved out pinning his knights.
He moved back and protected the king.
I took the knight beginning a trade for the pieces.
He took the bishop and gave me no advantage from the beginning places.
I threatened his knight and he would be forced to move.
He placed his knight in a position so that he could avenge his eventually dead rook.
I checked his king with my secondary plan.
He was forced to move in the only way he could have.
I took his rook and prepared for death.
He avenged and I was ready for his overdue attack.
I opened up the congestion in the middle prepared to defend.
He set up his pawns to avoid attack also.
I attacked to open the middle and was waiting for my rook to kill the king.
He opened his bishop and the middle for his rook.
I moved center already knowing my next move.
He took another pawn in my stair like position.
I took him to stop his wrathful pawn.
A swift check caught me off gaurd
I moved off the back line to avoid future complications
He redeveloped his knight after the previous defense.
I moved up allowing only one move for him
he was ready for a trade between us to stop thew attack.
I decided to do this and allowed my enemy to trade off
No Name took the piece and the center became officially open.
I threatened the opposing knight hoping he would move out.
The response was to put me in check instead.
I put myself out of check by moving forward a pawn.
He moved out of the way and challenged my piece.
I challenged his bishop also hoping the attack would draw him away.
He took it and fell back away from my king.
I advance with my pawns hoping that I could make it to the end.
With his knight trapped he moved out to attack my pawn.
I advanced on the knight knowing if I took the pawn he could escape.
He put me in check with the only way he could have
I escaped and still could take the knight
He protected his knight but gave me a head start to the other end.
I advanced upon the enemy lines.
He attempted to stop it.
I protected myself with the pawn.
His knight escaped though ruining my point.
I still protected my pawn though planning for a queen.
He set himself back to stop the attack.
I put him in check and forced action.
The best move for him in his eyes was to stop that pawn at risk of promotion
I took the obvious solution + ing him.
He escaped check though- easily.
I took a pawn unsure of what to do.
I was checked again and had to act.
Moved onto black escaping more.
He moved out a pawn stopping future promotion no matter what.
I took him to even the playing field.
He stopped me from advancing.
I protected the future attack with another pawn.
A pawn on the same line prevented motion.
I moved to open up future attacks for my bishop.
He began motion on his side.
I checked him with a single move.
He easily backed into the corner.
I continued to advance as fast as possible...
He put me in check though stopping it.
I stopped his pawn from promotion ending his line.
Having to move he moved his bishop.
I took his pawn and stopped motion almost completely.
He put my final able-to-move pawn in check.
I advanced a.s.a.p.
He threatened my bishop.
Sacrifice was necessary for this mission.
He took my piece off the board and I was ready for it.
I advanced and was ready for promotion.
He stopped production of my future pawn.
Nowhere to move I looked for the end.
He moved towards my pawn.
I stayed where I was- relatively
He moved infinitely closer.
Seeing my chance I sprung.
He was ahead a move and moved out.
I forked him. He had to choose.
He saved his bishop and attacked my nearside pawn.
I was ever-closer and was one step away.
He moved out leaving no congestion.
Promotion.
Nowhere to move he stumbled.
Fork. He was royally screwed.
He escaped check.
I took his bishop and he was in check yet again.
He escaped AGAIN and I was planned out.
Fork.
I was ready.
Only his king now.
He escaped downward.
No way out I was ready for mate.
He cooperated fully.
He was stuck and had no where to go So I took advantage.
Almost done.
Still cooperating he was ready to lose.
I nailed him and he had a forced position.
With his last strength he was already dead.
Getting ready.
Annoyed that I could have finished sooner I was tired.
A wall of pawns stopping him he took his last move.
Checkmate. Hope you enjoyed.

The game became a QGD

going in to some kind of a semi-slav. I dunno maybe this is one of the main linesi don't have any clue how Bogo-indian goes.

i think this was the best move.
Opening up the b-file for me and making my grip a bit stronger.

i ignored the fact that black can take the pawn. i didnt wanna become defensive. Instead i seize the b-file and putting an enourmous pressure on the b7-pawn.
black moved back with his bishop to defend the pawn.
Rb6. I have such a strong grip on the b-file and the b6-square that the next move is a little forced.

stopping Nb5 so that i can finally play Bd6.
Well.... i dont like that move because of....

well the only thing this does is controlling the h8-a1 diagonal.
attacking the rook.

i felt that i had a winning position here with my strong grip and material.
retreating the rook. I think i will win if i commence a Queen exchange because of my material but...

(the b-pawn was underfire since if i go Nxd7 it drags away the c8 bishop which is the defender of b7)

Rxb7!? i sacrifice a rook but i analyzed this position carefully and judged that i win.
Now queen gets dragged from the a1 rook which is the rook sacrifice.
heck he even takes that with check! but i have calculated this and i continued to play calm.
now even if this sac fails i get a bishop for a rook and it can become a draw.
to stop Qb8+ winning da rook.
this is what i am relying on. I calculated this very position and thought ''well why dont i advance with my a-pawn. unstoppable!
Rushing the queen back to the defense.
pushing that pawn another step.
if 32. Qxc8 Bxc8 33. a7 Bb7 followed by Kd7 and black gets solid. Even 32. e3 f6 33. Qxc8 Bxc8 34. a7 Bb7 and white can try 35. Ba6 but after 35. ... Ba8 there is no way for white to win.
Therefor i played Qb7. The main point is to push the a-pawn because 32. a7?? Qxb7. can anyone see.
he wanted to make room of his rook but i analyzed Qb6 deeply and i knew that i would win with the next move...
and now i expected him to play Qa8 here (only delaying my win!) but he played the blunder...
And after...

started with a d4 opening
transposed immediately in the english
in my opinion this defense is the safest. But i recognized that black will soon find problem on the queen side.
still nothing on the center. It is the plan. This black knight is one of the most important pieces in the game.

This is something I play a lot as I generally don't know what to do with this clear black bishop and the knights are dangerous pieces in the closed english
and now starts the real position where black goes on f-g columns and white on b-c.
oups... no... so did I lie? No: black just tries to block queen side as you will see. But it won't really work
white clearly views queen-side.
...and defend king-side
exits one knight
exit my dubious bishop. I won't cry for him. And his white bishop loses a move here. It will be important as we will see.
trying to open on the center. May be over confident as I haven't finished my development unlike white.
white closes the center. The battle really will be on the flanks.
he is a defender. Will not see the ocean on the king side.

now white has to make a bad choice: taking my bishop or saving his...

well it looks like I still have the same advantage considering the captured scale. And white still has his fine attack but there is much more than that. protecting g6
attacking g6 with potential e4-e5
protecting g6 but also and mostly pointing to e5.

I suppose white has no more passion in the game. Too bad because I wanted to try myself here...

Many people play this opening and it's a great opening. I used to play it all the time but I don't play it anymore. When I played it I never played a fianchetto on the g2 square. That's maybe the reason I had trouble with it. Not playing the fianchetto is still o.k but playing the fianchetto is better for attacking the center.
A common response to c4.
Still nothing wrong.
The first strange move of the game. As mentionned in another annotated game early queen moves are almost always bad since the queen will usualy get chased around.

This move does two things. It would later help support e4 and White already sees what black's plan: Mate on f2. It's a little early to play this move and Nf3 does exactly the same thing AND developes a piece. The big downside to this move is that it loses a pawn after Qh4+.
Black missed their chance (again). Black will be disappointed to know that the quick mate they were thinking of doesn't work.
A waste of a move. The plan for white is to chase away the bishop which is not a good plan.
Who want's free pawns? darkblue is giving them out for free!
Obviously _sarg_ doesn't want any. b4 isn't a bad move. White can take the pawn later.

Black sets up a small trap. If white takes the pawn with the g pawn it's mate with Qg4. If white takes the big pawn (bishop) black will win with the funniest mate of all time with f2! All white has to do is take the pawn with the knight.
White chose the wrong defence.
And in 6 moves black has won. Remember that this game was played in the casual section of the tournament. Congratulations to black for finally getting their revenge.
Classic white e4 developing.
The Queen's Fianchetto. To defend against a big White's pawn center and make it more difficult for White to play a c4 pawn break.
Classic move. White is building an advantage through the center.
Bishop development continuing the Fianchetto development
White often preferred developing his bishop to d3 rather than c4 b5 or Nc3.
Black offers a pawn to break White's pawn center.
White accepts the Pawn oppening the a8-h1 diagonal for the Bishop.
Check! This prevent Bishop from taking unprotected h1 tower.
Now Black is attacking the White Queen & the White Tower.
Excellent Move! If Black is ambitious and take White's Tower it's Checkmate by 7....  Bxh8  8.gxh7#
Black gets greedy and loses immediately.
Another excellent move! You can think black have an excellent game...
...happily eating the enemy Queen but he doesn't see the danger...
Checkmate! Even after four centuries some games can still elict a smile. Taken from Chessmaster 9000 Classic Games; Gioachinno Greco vs Unknown. Annotation from 1619.
A common move for white.
A common move for black.
A common 2nd move for white.
A common 2nd move for black.

Only three knights.
Loses a pawn.

Black missed their chance.
Not the best move. Black can't take the knight because the queen is pinned.
The losing move. I don't see a move that could be worse.
White sees the chance to win early
An 8 move mate. Remember that this game was played in the casual section of the tournament.
I don't think I've ever played an opening like that before and it progressed into the mid-game surprisingly fast
looking back me castling on the queen side was what made this game turn out like it did. This becomes visible towards the end of the game.
Swo0t! I love having twin bishops controlling the board.
here to stay
whoopsi so busy commencing D-day... didn't see that one coming
This move feels awkward now but it really pays off!

now I can march the pawns (preserved on the queen side because of the heat in the middle and castling there) forward. Getting my Bishop where I need it proves to be a significant hinge for the remainder of my game
This move was actually a mistake I made it without really thinking but what comes next is an even better mistake!
I was wowed that I still had that piece
game over for black just a matter of delaying the inevitable now
two checks serve nothing less than for me to further increase strength for my troops on the front line

at this point I didn't know how the mate would pull together and I was being really careful to not make any mistakes. thinking back this pawn/bishop/knight combo force turns out to be one of if not the most powerful end-game pushes I remember having ever played.
Lovely.

Hello i'd like to annotate this game because i found it fascinating...It was a game for the 5th round of 61st GK Tournament. I play with black here.
 So he started with e4.
I played e5. I always prefer that move instead of playing c5.
Typical.
And typical reply too. I don't like Nf6.
He played with his white bishop. Nice move.
I replied by opening the knight and pushing e4 pawn. I like to open the king's side pieces.
In order to protect the e4 pawn.
I open the bishop. I wanted to castle and also open my white bishop with d6 pawn.
We castled so far a quiet game. Noone is risking.
So he attacked in the e pawn and i accepted that nice move. He wanted to open the game and not being pathetic. i have the tendency as black to play a quiet game ( i prefer to play with white pawns).
So i took it.
I imagined that. Otherwise it would have been a bad move for him.
I decided to sacrifice the bishop! Bye bye Bishop! I think i made the right choice.
He took my bishop and he's queen has somehow a more attacking attitude.
I decided to open my queen too and protect my knight.
Now he's pushing the other knight but still i have no worries. Nice movement anyway.

It is not chess here just showcase of aggressiveness

And BxB. Of course do not accuse me of self-contradiction here for what I previously said about avoiding the unmeaning liquidation of material. Besides if I retreat the B then it can be positive for Black in light of obliging White's Q to stick to its position to prevent Qh1# now that f2 is not an escape square.
However when I saw the possibility of winning a pawn out of BxB I could not resist such a concrete advantage as a having an extra pawn.
So Q attacks both Rh1 and d4 pawn.
To my bad luck taking on d4 is not possible because of the discovered Bxh7+ check. However the fact that White's Ra was diverted from protecting the a-pawn came as a consolation to me.
And if the pawn advance I will bring Q to a.

Oups! What's going on ? I really hate surprises.
So I accepted the eventuality of a pawn on f6 in exchange for keeping the f-file closed.
This move frightened me as I thought there was something planned after my expected Rg8.
Thank God there was no threat. He just wants my rook to come there.
It was safe to do this I think.
The a6-pawn did not lure my opponent. So let's give him the e4 pawn.

What did I achieve from this manoeuvre ? Nothing except the realization that my extra-pawn advantage is a chimera. The exposure of Kg1 plays it its own safety While the pawn setup surrounding my king meant that at most I can keep a rook at the 8-th rank and bring two heavy pieces against White's three. Furthermore My King position somehow meant that manyy scenarios that involve the exchange of pieces would lead to unfavorable ending game.
And of course I had to face the immediate threat of Rh2 ( Followed by Qh attacking h7).  So here I was planning a solution that requires the exchange of Qs. How dramatic !
My only resort ; White is trying to attack the a pawn. I had to cure the passivity of my Q by exchanging the R that threatens Rh2.
Also White does not have other options. The complete exposure of his K is limiting his options with other pieces.
I am relatively in a safe position. But I had to solve the K-safety issue and then make use of the extra pawn.

I could not imagine another moment to do it. White's Q cannot touch the g file because of White's K being on the same g-file. Also the fact that Black Q can target e3 which is common to Kg1 and Rc1 implies that White's Q will be restricted in its choices.
I thought the victory is mine here by forcing Black to lose f6. Two choices were possible : either the Kh7 or the Rc6. I selected Rh7 and was expecting Rc2.
No he played c5.

I played this in view of the posibility to force White's K to be on h file then after my Kg6 I cumulate
to the existing threats on White's pawn the idea of Rh8+.

This really came as a shock to me. My head was telling this would only precipitate the plan of Kg6. However as R is still on f-file guarding f6 and Whites' Q able to play e4+ my king is in danger. I soon realized that my plan was incorrect and I have to cope with the inevitabilily of R+ and my K to tour the World. Now you can understand the title of the game.
So I played this more as a defense than as an attack. Q and R needed be connected as a means to secure the R from potential Q checks attacking both K and R.
And the journey began.

Many chess games against stronger player are unpleasant because you are getting tactically outplayed.  Often one gets the sinking sensation that the game is going to be a loss; that he will "take an L".  I have often counted it a principle to be sporting in such games.  Ultimately chess is about a search for perfection.  One values his knowledge of the game more than he clings to the spoils of any single victory.  In this sense since we stand to learn directly from our superiors in the game we should be grateful and even value the difficult positions that attend our encounters with our teachers...

Here I assessed my position as totally critical.  I am now almost certain that the game will be a loss.  I have not recovered from black's Nb4 and my own attacking prospects appear to be too little too late...
A desperate move to stave off Nxe3...
My queen is my worst piece having to recapture the knight on c1.  It is totally out of the game.  If possible I want to arrange the rousing Ne4 or Nf3...
The bishop could have been defended with Bf4 but then g5.  I am desperate to get the queen out...
Here black could've played more sharply with Qxe5...

I had seen that h3 was immune but black blunders massively in a won position and up 4 units of material.  If nothing else this game illustrates how in blitz it can be good to stick with a lost position.  I think that after Nb4 black relaxed a bit and didn't play accurately enough to keep me out of the game...

Hi everyone!

This is a game to illustrate that Knights on the Rim can be dim!  Adam a former Expert could not resist a little bit of pawn grabbing a sin I have sometimes been guilty of when I have done this against Freddy the Master Mater and paid with my king!  Adam was a little more fortunate his knight ended up getting coralled on the rim.  Adam had a potentially decisive kingside pawn majority.  I was taking no chances and so Henry did a royal progress up the chessboard and forced Adam to exchange pawns.  Adam was then left with a side pawn which Fou Lenoir captured and the game ended as a draw with neither players having sufficient material.  Computer Analysis for this game has been done so you can pick up my game in my past games profile and follow the game that way.  Black responds 1..... e6 to my e4 and so this becomes the French Defense.
3. ..... exd5 - this pawn trade gives this the Exchange Variation of the French Defense.
6. Bxc4 - smooth development so far.
7. ..... 0-0 - both sides tuck their respective kings on the kingside and now need to get their queenside pieces out.
10. g4 - this is recommended in the World DB but it does leave Henry a little draughty.
12. f4 - the beginnings of a pawn storm which does not quite materialise.
14. f5 - this pawn move triggers off several trades.
17. Rxe5 - I chose this recapture rather than dxe5 because I wanted to control the e column.
18. ...... Qc7 here comes the Wicked Witch of the West ssss - she is threatening Qg3+.  My queen Glenda The Defender moves one square to e1 to defend against this.
21. Qf2 - Glenda maintains control of g3 and gives a foothold for a rook to come to e1 and contest the e column.
22. Bb2 - Fou Lenoir finally emerges to defend the backward c3 pawn but to open a line for my rook to come to e1.
24. Qxe1 - the rooks have been traded off but it is difficult to see which player has the edge here.
25. Qe3 - preventing Nd3.

27. ...... Nxd5 - B for N trade.  It will be interesting to see just which piece is better.  Meanwhile Glenda decided to remind the BK that she is very interested in him when she is not tied down to defending - poor put upon Glenda!

30. Qf3 - I would have liked to have opened up the Bk with gxh5 here but unfortunately the Wicked Witch can land on g3 with a very nasty check mentioned in an earlier note.  So Glenda must defend it sigh!
34. Kf2 - Henry decided to move to give Glenda a foothold on the e column.  Now the Witch gives a series of checks.
37. Qf2 - after this little Royal merry-go round I offer a draw and Adam declines.  It seemed as though he had a winning plan but ....

40. Bd2! ..... yes but look at Fou Lenoir!  It seemed as though I had blundered a pawn because Henry had to move out of the way to avoid losing Fou Lenoir in a knight fork and therefore the a pawn fell but as you can see - at a price!  Fou Lenoir coralls the knight!
42. d5 - I decided to obtain a passer here but was it the right plan?
44. .... gxf5 - I did get a passer but alas so did black!

46. ...... Kc6 - my prized passer is about to fall but if K x P immediately Fou Lenoir will skewer the BK against that pawn.  The result will be a draw on the grounds of insufficient mating force.  That was exactly what happened and Adam and I had to manually agree a draw on move 49.  A pleasing result for me as it was a High Draw - my current form is very erratic but the more of these kind of results I get the more likely my rating may upsurge again should I be at the top of my game!

5... f5 ?! The starting position of my experimental line. I have searched the GK database and Lasha Janjgava's book "The Petroff" for this position. I can safely say this is an ignored continuation of the Classical Petrov. GK computer analysis indicates it is weak (-0.34) but apparently it is not a blunder. I am not discouraged by this score (yet) because "book" positions in other openings are similarly weak.

Not an unexpected response. OTB I have also seen 6. Bb5+ c6 7. Bd3. 

Edit: White avoids Nc3 Nxc3 bxc3 and the doubled pawns. Perhaps White SHOULD let Black double the pawns to gain breathing space?
The only viable move. Black's plan is simple - hold the 4th and 5th ranks with minimal pieces and develop quietly. The e4-Knight is meant to annoy rather than attack.
Black would rather not commit the pawn to d5 because a hole opens up on e5 but again this is the only viable move I have found so far.

White begins to chip away the edges of Black's stronghold. GK analysis gives White the advantage. This position resembles one typical of Petrov games except the Black Bishops are now on the e-file instead of the d-file.

Huge mistake here by White. GK analysis gives its best continuation as: 11. Nxe4 cxd3 12. Nc3 Bc4 13. Ne5 Bd5 14. Qxd3 Bb4 15. Nxd5 Qxd5 16. Re2 Na6 17. a3 Ba5 18. Bg5 Rae8 (-0.76). White's game goes downhill from here.

Black has attained full development the Bishop pair + Knight vs 2 Knights (1 pinned) + bad Bishop spatial advantage and a semi-open f-file. White has cleared the middle and grabbed the e-file with the Rook. However White has no immediate attacks against the exposed Black King and cannot expect to keep his isolani alive.
White still cannot capture the Bishop on h5 because of the threat to f2.
This move allows Black to neutralize White's active Rook as follows...
The Bishop temporarily cages the Rook while putting a bead on the White King.

The rest of the game is inconsequential so I will end the annotation here. This annotation was meant to stimulate discussion about the possibilities feasibility and flaws of the  5.f5?! line of the Classical Petrov. I use it in blitzes when possible but most players I meet here avoid the Classical Petrov completely with 3.Nc3. Have any other Petrov players explored this option? Please comment. Thank you.
